            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>
                How this construction framing and carpentry calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for quick, practical estimates on small
                residential and light commercial projects. It does not replace
                structural design or local code requirements, but it gives you a
                solid starting point for lumber lists and budgets.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Stud count for walls</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Convert wall length to inches</strong></p>
                <p>\( L_{in} = L_{ft} \times 12 \)</p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Base stud count</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( N_{stud,base} = \left\lfloor \dfrac{L_{in}}{S}
                  \right\rfloor + 1 \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \( S \) is stud spacing in inches (e.g. 16&quot; o.c.).
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Add corner and end studs</strong></p>
                <p>We add 2 extra studs for corners and layout adjustments.</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For openings, we add an allowance of extra studs per opening
                (king, jack and cripples). You can adjust the number of openings
                to better match your plan.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Plates and board feet</h3>
              <p>
                Plate length is simply wall length multiplied by the number of
                plates (bottom + one or two top plates). Board feet are
                estimated from nominal lumber sizes:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Board feet</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{BF} = \dfrac{T \times W \times L}{144} \)</p>
                <p>
                  where T and W are actual thickness and width in inches (e.g.
                  1.5&quot; × 3.5&quot; for a 2×4) and L is total length in
                  inches.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Joists, rafters and sheathing</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Joists / rafters:</strong> calculated the same way as
                  studs, using span or length and spacing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sheathing area:</strong> width × height (or run ×
                  length × roof slope factor).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sheets:</strong> area ÷ 32 sq ft per 4×8 sheet,
                  rounded up.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Waste factor</h3>
              <p>
                All counts and lengths are multiplied by
                <code>(1 + waste% / 100)</code> to account for cuts, defects and
                offcuts. Typical framing waste is 5–15% depending on complexity.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for framing and carpentry estimates</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Order by length:</strong> Once you know total linear
                  footage, break it into standard stock lengths (8, 10, 12, 14,
                  16 ft) to minimize waste.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check spans:</strong> Use manufacturer or code span
                  tables to confirm that your chosen size and spacing are
                  adequate for the loads.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Group similar walls:</strong> For a house, run the
                  wall calculator for each wall type (exterior 2×6, interior
                  2×4, bearing vs non-bearing) and then sum the results.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fasteners:</strong> The nail and screw counts here are
                  rough rules of thumb. Always follow the fastening schedule in
                  your plans or code.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and safety notes</h2>
              <p>This calculator is for estimating only. It does not:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Check structural capacity, deflection or vibration.</li>
                <li>
                  Account for point loads, large openings, beams or trusses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Replace stamped drawings from a licensed engineer where
                  required.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always verify your design with local building codes, span tables
                and a qualified professional before building.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Can I use this for metric framing?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can enter wall, floor and roof dimensions in meters,
                and the calculator converts internally. Spacing is still entered
                in inches on center, which is common even in many metric
                markets, but you can use the custom spacing field to match your
                layout.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I include double or triple studs at openings?</h3>
              <p>
                The openings field adds an allowance of extra studs per opening.
                For complex layouts (wide patio doors, grouped windows), use the
                result as a baseline and adjust manually from your detailed
                framing plan.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Does this handle engineered lumber (LVL, I-joists, trusses)?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. Engineered products have manufacturer-specific sizes, spans
                and spacing. You can still use the area and sheet counts from
                this tool, but follow the manufacturer’s design and takeoff
                guidance for the engineered members themselves.
              </p>
            </section>
